<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[117, 210, 918, 290]]<|/det|>
A particle \(P\) of mass \(m \mathrm{kg}\) is attached to one end of a light inextensible string of length \(2.6 \mathrm{m}\). The other end of the string is attached to a fixed point on a horizontal ceiling, and the string is taut. The particle is held in equilibrium by a force of magnitude \(35 \mathrm{N}\), acting in a vertical plane which is perpendicular to the ceiling and contains the string. The force acts in a direction perpendicular to the string (see diagram). The tension in the string is \(T \mathrm{N}\) and the vertical distance of \(P\) from the ceiling is \(2.4 \mathrm{m}\).  

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[117, 304, 545, 320]]<|/det|>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[119, 243, 918, 323]]<|/det|>
One end of a light inextensible string is attached to a particle \(A\) of mass \(3 \mathrm{kg}\). The other end of the string is attached to a particle \(B\) of mass \(4 \mathrm{kg}\). Particle \(A\) is in contact with a rough plane inclined at \(30^{\circ}\) to the horizontal, and particle \(B\) is in contact with a smooth horizontal plane. A second light inextensible string is attached to \(B\). The other end of this second string is attached to a particle \(C\) of mass \(5 \mathrm{kg}\) which hangs vertically.  

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[119, 336, 918, 385]]<|/det|>

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[119, 398, 918, 431]]<|/det|>
The system is released from rest. In the subsequent motion, \(C\) moves vertically downwards with acceleration \(2 \mathrm{m s}^{- 2}\), and neither \(A\) nor \(B\) reach a pulley.

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[117, 75, 918, 144]]<|/det|>
A particle \(P\) of mass \(3 \mathrm{~kg}\) is projected with a speed of \(8 \mathrm{~ms}^{-1}\) up a line of greatest slope of a rough plane inclined at \(30^{\circ}\) to the horizontal. \(P\) is projected from a point \(A\) on the plane and comes to instantaneous rest at a point \(B\) on the plane. \(P\) then slides back down the plane. The coefficient of friction between \(P\) and the plane is \(\frac{1}{12} \sqrt{3}\).

<|ref|>text<|/ref|><|det|>[[117, 163, 778, 179]]<|/det|>
Using an energy method throughout, find the speed of \(P\) at the instant it returns to \(A\).
